<DOCNO> AP890721-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the pilot of united airlines flight 232 
said he had almost no control over his dc10 in the final 34 
minutes before the jumbo jets fiery crash the national 
transportation safety board said thursday 
ntsb officials revealed a host of problems that plagued the 
illfated aircraft including the loss of fluid in the planes 
hydraulic system and holes in the tails horizontal stablizer 
at least 76 people were killed and up to 43 others were missing 
and believed dead in wednesdaysspectacular crash 
rescuers said many of those unaccounted for probably were 
trapped in a large silver and redstriped section of the charred 
fuselage that sat amid rows of corn 4 feet tall 
the dc10s hydraulic system which allow pilots to manipulate 
wing and tail controls contained no fluid as capt al c haynes 
tried to bring the plane into sioux gateway airport ntsb board 
member jim burnett told a news conference thursday night 
haynes notified federal aviation administration air traffic 
controllers in minneapolis at 324 pm cdt that he had almost no 
control over the aircraft burnett said 
the aircraft could only be turned to the right he said 
they made three 360degree turns the plane crashed at 358 pm 
the entire fanrotor system for one engine was missing burnett 
told a nighttime news conference thats the first time for this 
type of engine that weve ever seen 
ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz said there was a 
10inchby12inch hole and three or four smaller ones in the 
horizontal stabilizer the small horizontal wing on the tail 
section the rear engine sits just above the stabilizer 
lopatkiewicz said the holes were projectile penetrations 
but declined to be more specific such holes in the horizontal 
stabilizer could be caused by pieces of metal spewed like shrapnel 
from a disintegrating engine 
ntsb officials refused to answer questions about how any of the 
damage or failure of the hydraulic system would have contributed to 
the accident 
officials gave conflicting reports thursday on the number of 
survivors and the number of people aboard the aircraft with the 
number of survivors ranging from 174 to 197 
united later scaled back the high figure to 183 explaining that 
the flight crew had been mistakenly counted twice and that two 
people counted as survivors were now missing 
united and other officials said earlier there were 293 people 
aboard the dc10 but burnett said thursday night there were 295 
people on the aircraft he said there were four people in the 
cockpit instead of three including an offduty pilot asked about 
burnetts report united stuck by its figure of 293 
earlier thursday rescuers and survivors spoke of miracles and 
investigators swept inch by inch through a cornfield in the 
search for the crashs cause 
some survivors just walked away from the wreckage 
beginning at daybreak national guardsman began collecting 
pieces of wreckage and carrying body bags to ambulances and 
refrigerated trailers 
the plane crippled by the loss of hydraulic power pitched 
violently to its right just a few feet from the ground scraped its 
right wing cartwheeled into a ball of fire and broke into pieces 
during an emergency landing about 4 pm on a closed runway at the 
sioux gateway airport 
survivor garry priest 23 of northglenn colo said those who 
got out of the plane saw what looked like a war zone bodies 
trash magazines luggage and pieces of bodies littered the area 
it was the worst thing ive ever seen 
we could not believe anybody could walk away from it said 
dr david greco director of emergency services for the marian 
health center and one of the first physicians on the scene 
greco lauded the passengers and crew for maintaining calm and 
said the nature of the breakup of the plane largely determined the 
pattern of deaths and injuries 
the three members of the cockpit crew survived the crash but 
greco said the firstclass section was devastated passengers in 
rows nine through 19 suffered no injuries or minor ones he added 
but there was nothing left of the rear half of the aircraft 
one section was thrown so far so fast that it never got 
involved in the fire he said 
tales of heroism abounded beginning with praise for haynes a 
33year united veteran 
gov terry branstad visited haynes bedside and said at a news 
conference he was quite emotional about the situation and tears 
came to his eyes when he talked about the number of people who lost 
their lives i told him he did a valiant job 
in washington president bush extended his sympathy thursday to 
victims families and friends and praised the extraordinary 
efforts of rescuers at the crash site 
flight 232 from denver to philadelphia via chicago carried 11 
crew members and 282 passengers including three infants united 
spokesman lawrence nagin said earlier thursday the plane has a 
capacity of 287 passengers 
rachel halterman spokeswoman from the national transportation 
safety board said agency investigators met with emergency medical 
teams from the city county and state and representatives of the 
airline the planes manufacturer and the pilots union to maximize 
the search for victims and clues from the crash 
even the investigators cant say why so many people 
survived she said and there hasnt been time for 
speculation 
the search of the crash site roughly the length of three 
football fields will be an inchbyinch thing ms halterman 
said from the ntsbs makeshift command center in the sioux city 
convention center 
the flight recorder will be going back to washington sometime 
today and well start interviewing the crew and the survivors 
eyewitnesses and everybody we can who has firsthand knowledge of 
the accident she said were also collecting maintenance 
records on the plane 
two flight recorders which were not damaged in the crash were 
opened later in washington 
the flight voice recorder has the final 30 minutes of 
conversation from the dc10s cockpit and the data recorder 
contains several hours of information about the plane its speed 
compass heading and other data recorded every few seconds 
the recorder and tapes were in good condition said ntsb 
aeronautical engineer thomas jacky their contents are not likely 
to be made public for several weeks 
before the crash the pilot radioed to report that the 
15yearold jumbo jet experienced complete hydraulic failure 
federal aviation administration spokesman fred farrar said parts 
of the plane were found 50 miles away 
the tail engine failed which may have caused hydraulic failure 
said bob raynesford another faa spokesman the planes three 
independent hydraulic systems are routed to the tail section 
since the plane was not in one piece burnett said 
investigators could not say with certainty that the damaged engine 
was the one that the pilot had reported trouble with 
a modern jet engine works with a propellorlike fan encased in 
the engine housing the fan revolving at thousands of revolutions 
per minute draws in cold air to circulate around the combustion 
chamber and mix with hot exhaust gases in the rear of the engine 
for more use of fuel and a quieter engine 
inside the combustion chamber is a turbine which also has 
blades these blades are subject to far higher stresses and it is 
not uncommon for them to break 
the crash left a swath of charred runway and scattered bits of 
peoples lives over the wide expanse two sets of golf clubs a 
wallet photo of a brunette in her prom dress a reebok tennis shoe 
a purple hairdryer one black highheeled shoe and a collection of 
marilyn monroe photographs 
four people near alta 55 miles east of sioux city discovered a 
piece of the plane 6 to 7 feet high and 6 feet long in a 
cornfield 
virginia jane murray a flight attendant survived by crawling 
out of an opening in the burning wreckage 
she said she was tumbling said her father don murray of 
chester sc the walls were coming in she said a hole opened up 
and the sunlight came in and she climbed out the hole she said she 
knew the lord opened up that hole 
nineyearold yisroel brownstein suffered a broken arm and 
bruises but his parents who flew from denver to sioux city 
regarded the injuries almost joyously i feel like he was born 
all over again today said his father avrohom 
he wanted a broken arm like his friends he said now hes 
got one 
survivor mark michaelson of denver said that during the last 30 
minutes of the flight attendants drilled passengers on emergency 
procedures and told them to put their heads between their knees 
many survivors reported that the passengers were mostly calm as 
they prepared themselves for what they expected would be an 
extremely rough landing 
city manager hank sinda put the number of survivors at 174 
which with his count of 76 confirmed dead would put the number 
unaccounted for at 43 
uniteds count of the number of people who survived the crash 
fluctuated widely thursday by late evening the carrier scaled 
back its estimate of 185 survivors to 183 saying two people 
reported earlier as survivors were now unaccountedfor 
at one point airline spokesman russell mack put the number as 
high as 197 he later explained that the figure of 197 was a 
mistake he said he had been told the number had risen to 187 and 
including only passengers and that he added the flight crew to 
that figure 
</TEXT>
