<TEXT>
government records on the united dc10 that 
crashed in iowa are pretty clean with no major problems 
reported in recent years a spokeswoman for the federal aviation 
administration said 
the 15yearold jumbo jet had no accidents or reports of serious 
incidents during the past five years the amount of time covered in 
the agencys current records according to bobbie mardis in the 
faas oklahoma city office 
a separate faa service difficulty report covering 1980 to 1989 
showed two occasions when an engine on the jet flamed out or quit 
during flight no structural damage was evident in either case ms 
mardis said thursday 
connections cannot be immediately made between those engines and 
the ones now on the plane because officials havent identified the 
serial numbers of the engines in iowa ms mardis said 
but she said the engines on the jet most likely are different 
from those that experienced flameouts in 1980 and 1984 because 
they are replacing engines all the time 
she also said it is not uncommon for jets to experience engine 
flameouts and engines do not have to be replaced because of them 
the report looks pretty clean ms mardis said 
officials in sioux city reported late thursday that the planes 
tail engine failed and an engine fanrotor system was lost the 
planes tail wing also sustained several projectile 
penetrations including one hole 10by12 inches they said 
