<TEXT>
twelve former tamil guerrillas took 
their seats in parliament today ending a fivemonth boycott by 
disavowing a separatist campaign to divide this troubled island 
nation 
we come here today in the hope of using parliament as a forum 
to propagate on behalf of the tamil people although we do not 
think parliament can resolve the ethnic problems of this country 
said eliyathamby ratnasabapathy of the eelam revolutionary 
organization of students 
tamil rebels have been fighting the sinhalesedominated 
government for six years violence by sinhalese radicals opposed to 
a plan to grant regional autonomy to tamils has left more than 470 
people dead in recent weeks the government said thursday 
ratnasabapathy was among 13 members of the opposition party 
elected to the 225seat parliament the 13th did not attend todays 
session colleagues said because he could not arrive on time they 
did not elaborate 
the opposition party known as eros won its seats in the feb 
15 general election the legislators boycotted the session 
demanding the government release tamil political prisoners hold 
peace talks with the most militant guerrillas and abolish an 
amendment to the constitution requiring lawmakers to take an oath 
disavowing the division of the island along ethnic lines 
ratnasabapathy said the group was satisfied the government met 
most of its demands 
president ranasinghe premadasas government opened peace talks 
with the tamil tigers on may 4 the first direct contact since the 
insurgency began six years ago and ordered the release of hundreds 
of tamil political prisoners the constitutional amendment 
however was not abolished 
eros is widely believed to be closely linked with the liberation 
tigers of tamil eelam the largest and most militant of the tamil 
groups waging a campaign for a separate nation in the north and 
east 
ratnasabapathy and the other eros members joined parliament as 
it was debating whether to extend the state of emergency imposed a 
month ago to try to curb ethnic violence emergency laws are not 
going to solve any problems of the people the government will have 
to use democratic methods to bring about a solution he said 
the emergency laws had been in effect from 1983 until january 
1989 when premadasa took office and lifted the state of emergency 
but the killings continued and the emergency was reimposed june 20 
sinhalese radicals trying to overthrow the government killed 472 
people in recent weeks despite a tough new crackdown by security 
forces an official said vincent perrera minister for 
parliamentary affairs said thursday that the killings occurred 
from june 21 to july 15 
most deaths since july 6 had not been previously reported 
because of government censorship of news reports in addition to 
censorship the government gave security forces sweeping powers 
including shootonsight orders to quell the radical movement 
perrera also said that 70 people were killed in the 
tamildominated north and east during the same period he did not 
name the suspected assailants 
sinhalese militants operate mainly in the center and south of 
the island 
tamil rebels began fighting for a separate country in 1983 
prompting the start of the emergency laws 
in 1987 the sinhalesedominated government offered the rebels 
limited autonomy in exchange for a surrender of arms but the 
tigers rejected the plan and began fighting indian soldiers who had 
been sent to enforce it 
the agreement also caused a backlash from sinhalese hardliners 
who began attacking the government saying it was giving too many 
concessions to the minority tamils the two conflicts have left at 
least 15000 people dead 
