<TEXT>
investigators probing the destruction of 
united flight 232 focused today on the planes tail section and 
rear engine which apparently exploded in flight 
a severe engine explosion may have destroyed the hydraulic 
system that powers primary control mechanisms on the triplejet 
dc10 that crashed wednesday at sioux city iowa james burnett of 
the national transportation safety board said on cbs this 
morning 
but he said on nbcs today show we have to assemble a 
lot more information before well even get close to the cause of 
this accident 
there was a severe explosion enough that the flight 
attendants fell to the floor burnett told a news conference late 
thursday there was severe vibration of the aircraft the chief 
flight attendant went into the cockpit found the flight crew 
struggling with the controls 
the crew then began preparing the passengers for an emergency 
land he said 
ntsb investigators were attempting to recover remaining pieces 
of the engine whose parts were flung up to 60 miles ahead of the 
emergency landing site 
burnett said on abcs good morning america that eight groups 
of investigators were working in sioux city with others traveling 
to minneapolis to interview air traffic controllers who 
communicated with the flight and to san francisco to look at 
maintenance records for the aircraft 
in washington safety board engineers and scientists were going 
over tapes from the cockpit voice recorder and the planes digital 
data recorder which aeronautical engineer thomas jackey said were 
recovered in good condition from the tail section both were 
encased in apparently undamaged orange metal boxes 
the data recorder contains several hours of information about 
the plane its speed compass heading and other data recorded 
digitally every few seconds 
the voice recorder has the last half hour of conversation in the 
cockpit but a transcript is not expected to be released for 
several weeks investigators also were interviewing witnesses 
including the three cockpit crew members who survived the crash 
along with about twothirds of the nearly 300 passengers 
officials were still trying to get a final count on the number 
of dead and the number who struggled free from the wreckage 
investigators and aviation experts speculated that several 
factors aided those passengers who survived the tumbling of the 
plane which had the effect of lessening the impact the fact that 
the pilot had time to prepare passengers for a crash landing the 
quick breakup of the plane that opened up wide exits and the fact 
that a large section was thrown free of the fireball that engulfed 
parts of the aircraft 
a safety board official who discussed the investigation on 
condition of anonymity said the investigative agency was focusing 
initially on the tail section because that was the location of the 
engine whose explosive failure apparently started the problem 
the dc10s three independent hydraulic systems come together at 
their closest point in the same area of the plane 
douglas aircraft spokesman don hanson said the systems which 
are essential to control flight takeoff and landing are designed 
so that the plane can fly even if two of the three fail but ntsb 
member burnett said late thursday that all fluid had drained from 
the systems 
design of the dc10 has long been controversial with some 
aviation safety activists declaring it unsafe 
john galipault of the aviation safety institute a nonprofit 
group that pushes for safer planes said the crash underscores 
serious problems in dc10 design 
he said the common element in several dc10 crashes and 
incidents has been loss of some or all of the pilots ability to 
control the aircraft after a catastrophic failure in a single 
system 
when that happens the pilot becomes a passenger he said 
it reinforces my concern about the airplane its too bad but it 
has a terrible safety record 
in 1974 loss of a cargo door caused decompression in a turkish 
airlines dc10 over france the planes floor buckled snapping 
control cables and the airliner went out of control killing 346 
people 
on may 25 1979 in chicago the engine of an american airlines 
dc10 broke loose and catapulted over the wing during takeoff 
breaking hydraulic cables and causing a crash that killed 275 
people investigators blamed faulty maintenance but recommended a 
design review 
mcdonnell douglas spokesman david eastman said he knew of only 
one design change that has occurred in the dc10 since the chicago 
crash involving instrumentation that would warn the pilot when 
wing slats were improperly positioned 
