<TEXT>
teachers salaries have been on the rise since 
the early 1980s but their purchasing power is only slightly higher 
than in 1972 the american federation of teachers said friday 
the average 198889 salary of 29629 an alltime high is 
737 higher than the average 1972 salary when adjusted for 
inflation the union said in releasing its annual earnings survey 
salaries have risen considerably in the 1980s including 55 
percent since last year but trying to recover the salary high 
water mark is as motivating as trying to get ahead on a 
treadmill aft president albert shanker said in a statement 
he calculated that all raises teachers have received since 1972 
average out to 41 a year 
thats obviously not enough to pay a mortgage or provide for 
ones family and its certainly not enough of an incentive to 
enter teaching shanker said 
the unions 50state survey is based on information from state 
education departments it said the 1972 average teacher salary was 
9702 amounting to 28892 in 1988 dollars or only slightly less 
than current earnings 
salaries across the country range from alaska at 41832 to 
south dakota at the bottom with 20525 the aft said 
fourteen states reported starting salaries exceeding 20000 and 
four idaho north dakota south dakota and west virginia had 
starting salaries below 16000 five states alaska california 
connecticut hawaii and new york reported firstyear wages of 
more than 22000 
the rival national education association reported similar 
findings in a teacher salary study released in march the aft 
conclusions also were consistent with the education departments 
latest wall chart a statebystate comparison of education 
indicators issued in may 
