<TEXT>
in an unprecedented appearance marshal sergei 
f akhromeyev the soviet unions preeminent military figure told 
a house committee today that us reluctance to negotiate 
reductions in its naval forces is a serious obstacle to arms 
control in all other areas 
akhromeyev said the soviet union suspects the united states is 
interested in large cuts in conventional land forces in europe in 
order to gain overall military superiority over moscow 
specifically he said the kremlin fears that after such a 
conventional arms reduction agreement the united states would 
build up its naval forces without any constraints especially its 
carrier battle groups 
thus he told the house armed services committee the united 
states would gain military superiority in order to dictate its 
will to the ussr from a position of strength 
we regard reaching agreement on starting the talks to reduce 
our naval forces and limit military activities at sea to be a major 
prerequisite for further improvement of sovietamerican relations 
and switching them on to really peaceful rail tracks akhromeyev 
said 
in a lengthy statement read with the aid of an interpreter 
akhromeyev returned to the subject of naval forces several times 
he said the kremlin believes that reducing land forces while 
maintaining the size of naval forces or actually increasing them is 
unjust 
if you follow this line no drastic reductions of the armed 
forces and armaments in the world will be possible the soviet 
marshal said 
he said naval reduction talks should be started first by the 
soviet union and the united states and later by the north atlantic 
treaty organization and the warsaw pact 
conditions should be created for the whole range of armed 
services and armaments of the two sides to become the subject of 
the talks and subsequent talks he said 
akhromeyev who retired last year as chief of the soviet general 
staff is now chief military adviser to soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev 
he was welcomed to the armed services committee by chairman les 
aspin dwis who told him never has so highranking a soviet 
official appeared before a congressional committee through the 
years we have seen many uniforms sit at that table but never one 
like yours 
the soviet marshal his olive brown uniform trimmed with stripes 
of red and more than a dozen rows of military ribbons testified in 
a hearing room decorated with the portraits of former armed 
services committee chairman and flags of the us military services 
aspin invited ahromeyev to testify as one of a series of 
appearances before the committee by soviet military officers and 
defense experts 
some conservative members of the committee and other lawmakers 
have called it inappropriate that the soviets be given such a 
sounding board but aspin has said such witnesses provide a unique 
window into official soviet thinking 
akhromayev received a cordial reception from the committee 
today and no members raised questions over the propriety of his 
appearance 
akhromeyev offered what appeared to be a detailed accounting of 
soviet military spending and troop and weapons strngth 
he said his country will spend 84 percent of its gross national 
product 773 billion rubles on its military forces he said the 
united states will spend 54 percent of its gnp during the same 
period 
as of the middle of 1989 the ussr possesses 1398 icbm 
launchers with a little over 6000 warheads deployed on those 
launchers akhromeyev said 
he also listed 60 submarines with 920 launch tubes for 
sealaunched ballistic missiles 160 heavy bombers and a certain 
number of longrange submarinebased sealaunched cruise 
missiles 
all in all the soviet union possesses 2484 strategic carriers 
with about 10000 warheads deployed on them he said 
as of the beginning of the year akhromeyev said soviet ground 
forces numbered 1596 million troops 
he said that will have been reduced unilaterally by 300000 men 
to about 1296 million troops by the beginning of 1991 
he repeated soviet opposition to the development of a us star 
wars antimissile system but said the soviet union remains 
committed to deep cuts in strategic and conventional arms 
we intend to keep our strategic nuclear forces approximately 
equal to the us strategic offensive forces and we do not intend 
to gain superiority in this field he said 
akhromeyev said at several points that a very favorable 
atmosphere of trust and decreased military tension has developed 
in recent years 
he called for more exchanges between us and soviet military 
officers and for further appearances by soviet officials before 
congress and exchanges between the house armed services committee 
and the defense committee of the supreme soviet the soviet 
parliament 
