john a knauss a former professor has been 
picked to head the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
an agency he helped create 19 years ago 
the white house said friday that president bush has selected 
knauss for the post bushs nomination is subject to senate 
confirmation 
knauss 63 is a former dean of the university of rhode islands 
graduate school of oceanography 
he was named undersecretary of commerce for oceans and 
atmosphere which oversees noaa the agency has 12000 employees 
and an annual budget of 13 billion and includes the national 
weather service and the national marine fisheries service 
in 1968 president johnson appointed knauss to the stratton 
commission which recommended putting all oceanrelated units under 
one agency noaa was formed two years later 
knauss was recruited as dean of the uri oceanography school in 
1962 from the university of californias scripps oceanography 
institute he retired from that post in 1987 
he also served beginning in 1978 on the national advisory 
committee on oceans and atmospheres that advised the president and 
congress on technical matters he chaired that group from 198185 
i am pleased and excited about the possibilities of 
administering what is clearly the most important environmental 
program in the federal government at a time when the nation is 
giving increased attention to environmental problems knauss said 
in an interview with the providence ri journalbulletin 
several other candidates had been considered but knauss was 
favored from the start because of his excellent background 
said bj cooper deputy white house press secretary 
since midjune knauss has been shuttling between washington and 
his north kingstown ri home 
i dont see coming in and making big changes or big waves 
knauss said in a recent interview with the journalbulletin i 
would hope that the bush administration is more concerned with 
environmental problems than the previous administration was 
knauss is well known in professional circles as an oceanographer 
and meterologist who helped define the modern practice of 
oceanography 
