<TEXT>
david langs wheat field looks green and 
almost lush waving gently in a breeze that provides a momentary 
respite from north dakotas july inferno 
but langs digging fingers find surface soil so dry it runs like 
salt through his fingers deeper where the ground in better times 
would come up in moist dark clumps it is pale almost as hard as 
a nearby fence post 
the wheat stalks hold little promise of developing plump 
healthy kernels in time for the august harvest 
you get down here theres nothing there lang said his 
fingers probing the parched dirt 
this is the second straight drought year for north dakota and 
langs farm about 23 miles east of bismarck is in one of the 
states driest areas 
the drought of 1989 is not as widespread as the previous year 
but it still covers roughly a third of the nation said norton 
strommen chief meteorologist for the us agriculture department 
the main swath cuts northwest from illinois through the dakotas 
parts of kansas and nebraska strommen said 
virtually all of north dakota the nations leading producer of 
spring wheat and durum a wheat variety used for pasta is 
considered to be in a severe to extreme drought he said parts 
of neighboring south dakota and minnesota also have been hurt 
at this time to get back down to near normal it would 
take from 5 to 10 inches of rain strommen said 
but that much rain is unlikely on the 3100acre farm that lang 
43 works with his 78yearold father theodore 
on monday storms dumped as much as 3 inches of rain on some 
parts of the state but said lang it missed us 
the lang farm has gotten only about 4 inches of rain since 
april 1 about half of what the thirsty soil needs 
there isnt any subsoil moisture said theodore lang a 
state representative since 1965 and a lifelong farmer thats 
where the problem is 
the wheat field david lang surveys may yield three or four 
bushels an acre a sixth of its normal yield and barely enough to 
make harvesting worthwhile 
last summer it held on for so long lang said i guess 
thats what kept your optimism up because youd look out in the 
field and it was still green youd think gee if you could just 
get a halfinch of rain on this 
rain was in short supply everywhere in north dakota last year 
when about a third of the states 62 millionacre spring wheat 
crop was abandoned direct crop losses were estimated at more than 
500 million 
north dakota state university researchers have pegged this 
years crop losses at 661 million so far saying the state would 
lose 30 percent of its spring wheat and from 26 percent to 42 
percent of its durum barley and hay 
the 1988 drought ruined langs crop but this spring in hopes 
of plentiful rainfall and prices driven up by grain shortages he 
planted 1500 acres 
now he estimates he may be able to harvest only about 150 acres 
there are some bright spots lang expects to have enough hay to 
feed 150 cattle and the cattle can graze fields that would be 
useless to harvest the farm is not in danger of foreclosure 
wearing jeans and a denim shirt with cutoff sleeves exposing 
popeyesize forearms lang maintains a sunny disposition 
i guess im more of an optimist he says 
but he worries whether the federal government which pumped more 
than 400 million in drought aid into north dakota last year will 
respond again in 1989 when dry conditions are not as widespread 
nationwide 
lang received about 25000 in federal drought aid last year 
that aid along with cropinsurance payments helped keep the wolf 
off our back he said 
i dont want to see a handout im not begging for a 
handout lang said but you look at what disaster money did to 
the economy of north dakota last year some of the areas were 
going to need it to keep things going 
</TEXT>
