to the disbanded paramilitary unit known as koevoet the afrikaans 
word for crowbar 
i want to totally remove the shadow of koevoet he told a 
news conference in namibia 
during that territorys war koevoet members often went on 
weeklong patrols through isolated villages and bush territory in 
armored vehicles mounted with machine guns they were accused of 
dozens of atrocities against civilians and guerrillas 
koevoet was officially disbanded earlier this year but more 
than 2000 of its members were integrated into the regular police 
force swapo says those members are still harassing its supporters 
in lusaka zambia swapo president sam nujoma said south 
africancontrolled namibian troops killed 27 civilians near 
oshakati in northern namibia 
he said villagers reported seeing former koevoet members burying 
the victims corpses after the july 15 killings 
he called the killings a massacre but gave no details 
the people were murdered they koevoet were really caught 
redhanded said nujoma at a news conference 
territorial authorities previously acknowledged burying 11 
guerrillas but dismissed the report of 27 bodies 
nujoma said the killings support swapos demands for an increase 
in the strength of un forces supervising the independence plan 
about 4650 un troops now are stationed in namibia under the plan 
nujoma urged the united nations to send more troops to namibia 
so its forces could be in a position to prevent further south 
african massacres of our people and intimidation of voters 
swapo is favored to win the elections 
pienaar met with perez de cuellar on wednesday and announced 
that former koevoet members would be moved from northcentral 
namibia into less tense regions but he says he will dismiss 
policemen only if misconduct is proved against them individually 
perez de cuellar also said friday he was very much concerned 
by charges that swapo continues to hold large numbers of prisoners 
at camps in angola under terms of the un independence plan 
political prisoners on both sides are to be freed and 24 swapo 
members were released from a namibian prison thursday 
swapo has said it released all 201 detainees it held but 
relatives and the freed detainees have said nearly 2000 prisoners 
were in swapo camps 
the former detainees also say dozens of people were killed in 
the camps 
perez de cuellar said he plans to travel to zambia on saturday 
to confer with president kenneth kaunda and nujoma 
