<TEXT>
an evenly divided house ways and means 
committee failed friday in a new effort to decide the fate of 
catastrophic health insurance for older americans 
on an 1818 vote the committee defeated an amendment by rep 
willis gradison rohio that would have allowed a beneficiary to 
avoid paying a tax to finance catastrophic coverage so long as he 
or she also forfeited medicare coverage for physicians fees 
medicare coverage of doctors fees known as part b is heavily 
subsidized by the government although beneficiaries pay a premium 
of 2790 a month part b is voluntary but current law requires 
every person eligible for medicare to enroll in catastrophic 
twelve democrats and six republicans voted for the amendment 11 
democrats and seven republicans voted no 
the committee ended its work for the week without resolving 
another major issue whether to reduce the tax on capital gains 
aides said six democrats and the 13 republicans favor a plan to 
reduce the tax which applies to profits from the sale of stocks 
and other assets 
president bush wants a cut in the rate 
rep dan rostenkowski dill the committee chairman and house 
speaker thomas s foley dwash oppose a reduction because most 
of the benefit would go to those with income of more than 100000 
a year they also fear cutting the rate would be the first step 
toward unraveling the massive 1986 tax overhaul which took away 
any preference for capital gains 
rostenkowski and foley while opposing a rate cut are exploring 
the possibility of cutting capitalgains taxes another way by 
indexing the system so that gains that were caused solely by 
inflation are not taxed 
catastrophic coverage under medicare was enacted a year ago to 
help insulate older americans against having their savings eroded 
by medical expenses it is under attack because twothirds of the 
cost of the program is paid by those 65 and older who have enough 
income that their federal income taxes exceed 150 
in 1989 the maximum catastrophic tax is 800 or 1600 if both 
spouses are eligible for medicare 
some who are having to pay the surtax have been complaining so 
loudly that congressional leaders say the program will have to be 
changed 
a move for outright repeal was rejected by the ways and means 
committee thursday 
in addition to defeating the gradison proposal friday the 
committee beat a proposal by rep hank brown rcolo that would 
have eliminated coverage of drugs under the catastrophic plan and 
used the money saved to cut the surtax the surtax rate now 15 
percent of income taxes over 150 would have been cut to about 2 
percent committee aides said 
the bush administration like rostenkowski would prefer that 
the program be left as is committee aides said the administration 
supported gradisons proposal and could support a rostenkowski 
substitute that would keep the program intact but dump a greater 
share of the cost onto older people with incomes under 25000 a 
year 
