<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency stopped 
work on a report about oil drilling damage in alaska just before a 
senate committee was to vote on opening the states arctic national 
wildlife refuge to drilling epa officials said friday 
sylvia lowrance director of epas solid waste office said she 
issued a stopwork order on the report about the damages wastes 
from drilling were causing to alaskas north slope because she 
found a preliminary draft poorly written and organized 
the report concluded that oil wastes seeping from drilling pads 
leaking chemical drums and overflowing waste disposal pits were 
seriously damaging the environment in the prudhoe bay area 
although it appeared to contain a good deal of information it 
was difficult to distinguish governmental views from those of other 
sources ms lowrance told the house energy and commerce 
subcommittee on transportation and hazardous materials 
but the subcommittees chairman rep thomas a luken dohio 
alleged that epa may have suppressed the report because its 
disclosure to the public embarrassed the epa top brass who 
sympathized with the oil industry 
ms lowrance issued the stopwork order on the report on march 6 
a week before the senate energy and natural resources committee 
was to vote on opening up 15 million acres of the arctic national 
wildlife refuge to drilling 
located about 70 miles east of the prudhoe bay field now 
responsible for about 22 percent of the nations oil production 
the area is viewed by petroleum geologists as the last major 
untapped oil field in north america 
the senate panel in midmarch approved a phased program for oil 
and gas leasing in the refuge but the legislative effort quickly 
ground to a halt after the exxon valdez oil tanker spill on march 
24 
epa officials in ms lowrances office said they recommended on 
april 11 that work on the north slope report be resumed it was 
published in june 
both reports concluded there are problems with waste 
management on the north slope ms lowrance said 
but she said the second report cites specific cases of damages 
needed by government regulators to justify crafting any 
regulatory changes judged necessary those specifics were missing 
in the original draft she said 
other epa officials also noted that the second report put more 
emphasis on efforts by state officials in alaska to address the 
problem of hazardous wastes from oil drilling 
the north slope report is the first of nine commissioned by the 
epa to develop guidelines for state regulators on controlling 
wastes from oil and natural gas drilling 
the reports were commissioned after the agency declared last 
summer that drilling wastes do not fall into a hazardous 
category requiring regulation by the federal government 
congress in 1980 specifically exempted the oil gas and mining 
industries from federal hazardous waste regulation but ordered epa 
to study the issue with specific directions to weigh how much it 
would cost them if covered 
epa estimated the cost to the oil industry of meeting hazardous 
waste standards at 200 million to 500 million a year but said 
they could go much higher if drillers also had to pay for cleaning 
up past disposal sites 
