<TEXT>
the transportation department retreated friday 
from a muchcriticized proposal to regulate anhydrous ammonia as a 
poisonous gas and offered a compromise to change only the labeling 
on tanks of the commonly used fertilizer 
agricultural groups and farmstate lawmakers opposed the 
departments original 1987 proposal to change the regulatory 
classification of anhydrous ammonia saying it would drive up 
prices of the nitrogen fertilizer for farmers by increasing 
shipping and insurance costs 
in the face of those objections the department unveiled a new 
proposal that would continue to classify anhydrous ammonia as a 
nonflammable gas but require tanks and other containers to 
carry an inhalation hazard label the new marking would be in 
addition to the nonflammable gas label currently required 
the original proposal would have required anhydrous ammonia to 
carry a warning placard of inhalation hazard and a white 
diamond sign with a skull and crossbones 
the agency will publish its latest proposal in the federal 
register next week and will open a 90day period for comment a 
final decision on the regulatory rulemaking would be made later 
although there is no deadline according to a department spokesman 
on capitol hill farmstate lawmakers applauded the departments 
compromise 
well live with this said rep pat roberts rkan who 
helped lead congressional opposition to the poisonous gas 
classification we finally got the message through and won a 
little victory 
farmers apply anhydrous ammonia directly to the soil with corn 
and wheat producers among the main farm users 
although there is no dispute that anhydrous ammonia can cause 
injury or even death if it is inhaled at high concentrations 
opponents of the regulatory change argued that the pronounced odor 
of the gas acts as a warning even at low concentrations and helps 
prevent undue exposure in the event of a leak or accident 
</TEXT>
