<TEXT>
the mclaughlin group does not need to 
provide equal time to political candidates whose opponents appear 
on the show in videotaped news clips the federal communications 
commission said friday 
the commission in a 30 vote upheld a decision by the fccs 
mass media bureau that the shows news reporting segments of 
candidates may qualify as newscasts and therefore are exempt from 
the equal opportunity requirements of the 1934 communications act 
oliver productions the shows producer asked in october 1988 
that the commission make such a ruling which follows earlier fcc 
decisions exempting interview shows such as the macneillehrer 
newshour and meet the press from the equal opportunity 
provision 
oliver attorney david liebowitz said were gratified with 
the ruling he said the shows use of clips may be unique and that 
the fccs decision may not apply to other newstalk shows 
on the mclaughlin group host john mclaughlin briefly 
introduces a news reporting segment that uses videotaped news 
clips of candidates oliver told the commission the clips are 
selected on the basis of their news value 
oliver said there was no intent to advance the candidacy of any 
particular individual 
the telecommunications research and action center a 
washingtonbased advocacy group argued that the bureau had 
misinterpreted the strictures of the communications act 
but the commission agreed with the bureaus conclusion that the 
news reporting segments satisfied all the criteria for the 
newscast exemption and therefore that the segments were exempt 
from the equal opportunity provisions of the act 
section 315 of the communications act says that if a broadcaster 
permits a legally qualified candidate for public office to use a 
stations facilities it must give equal opportunities to all other 
candidates for that office 
but congress in 1959 amended the act to exempt newscasts news 
interviews shows documentaries in which the candidates appearance 
is incidental to the subject being covered and onthespot news 
events 
</TEXT>
