<TEXT>
a state task force friday conditionally 
approved spending nearly 45 million on the university of utahs 
fledgling coldfusion research program 
the ninemember state fusionenergy council voted unanimously to 
give the university the money once a final linebyline review of 
the schools proposed fusion budget is completed 
once that is done probably in a week or so the proposal will 
go back to the full panel for final approval 
since march when university of utah chemist b stanley pons and 
british colleague martin fleischmann announced theyd achieved a 
sustained nuclear fusion reaction in a laboratory flask scientists 
have attempted to duplicate the experiment with mixed results 
a federal energy panel recommended july 12 against new 
government efforts to verify the research saying there was no 
convincing evidence of a new nuclear fusion process that would be a 
useful source of energy 
despite sharp criticism from the scientific community 
university officials steadfastly have defended the experiments to 
the council which is charged with deciding whether to disburse a 
5 million legislative appropriation toward further research 
as part of its twoyear budget request the university asked 
funding for research laboratory space recruitment of outside 
scientists administration and other costs said james brophy the 
schools vice president for research 
before the vote university president chase peterson urged the 
council to act quickly to keep utah from relinquishing its lead in 
the development of fusion as an energy source and to avoid losing 
potentially lucrative commercial contracts 
utah has an opportunity to become a leader in the nation 
in developing a new science concept he said 
fusion involves the combining of atoms as contrasted with 
fission or the splitting of atoms that is used to produce nuclear 
power 
pons and fleischmann have said their experiments have produced 
up to 150 times the energy put into them generating the excess 
heat that is considered key to fusions potential as an alternative 
energy source 
