<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday upheld a 
preliminary injunction that bars the government from excluding a 
palestinian man from the united states 
ruling in the case of fouad rafeedie of cleveland the appeals 
court said that us district court judge joyce green must decide 
whether immigration procedures the us government is using against 
rafeedie violate his right to due process under the constitution 
in its 21 ruling the appeals panel said immigration officials 
may proceed against rafeedie under another provision of federal 
law which allows him to be represented by legal counsel to 
present evidence and to challenge witnesses in an open 
administrative hearing 
rafeedie a permanent resident alien who has lived outside 
cleveland for 13 years traveled to syria in 1986 attending the 
meeting of an organization affiliated with the popular front for 
the liberation of palestine a terrorist group immigration 
officials say 
rafeedie who denies he was affiliated with the group was 
questioned by the fbi on his return and in 1987 was charged with 
being excludable from the united states under immigration laws 
the immigration and naturalization service then attempted to 
expel him under the summary exclusion provision of the 
mccarranwalter act 
under that provision the ins gave rafeedie no indication of the 
nature of confidential information on which it sought to exclude 
him and rafeedie isnt entitled to a hearing 
rafeedies lawyer david cole of the center for constitutional 
rights said he is confident the us district court will find that 
the procedure violates due process 
