<TEXT>
the senate voted to make it easier for soviet 
jews and evangelical christians as well as ukrainians and 
vietnamese to enter the united states as refugees 
sen frank lautenberg dnj who authored the measure said it 
would relieve the backup of more than 4000 soviet refugees who 
were stranded in rome after they were denied entry to the united 
states 
the senate passed the measure thursday night as an amendment to 
a state department authorization bill 
lautenberg said the amendment would reduce the standard of proof 
required of some foreigners seeking to enter the country on grounds 
of persecution 
at the direction of former attorney general edwin meese iii the 
immigration and naturalization service last year began considering 
each refugee application on a casebycase basis the ins revoked 
old rules that had assumed applicants from certain countries were 
persecuted 
under the meese directive the onus was on applicants to prove 
they had a well grounded fear of persecution but meese did not 
specify how this fear could be proven 
lautenbergs bill sets criteria to determine eligibility among 
the criteria the applicant may try to show he or she was denied 
employment entry into educational institutions or prohibited from 
studying or practicing religion 
it doesnt make sense to ignore the historic and continuing 
pattern of persecution faced by most soviet jews evangelical 
christians ukrainians and vietnamese lautenberg said the 
very fact that someone belongs to one of these groups means that 
they have a very real fear of persecution 
the united states should continue to be a safe haven for those 
who are persecuted by their governments for their race religion or 
political beliefs he said 
lautenberg said a study by the congressional general accounting 
office found that denial rates for soviet jews increased from 7 
percent in 1988 to about 38 percent in march and 21 percent in june 
under the changed policy 
the new jersey senators amendment would establish a special 
category for those refugees for 1989 and 1990 and would allow 
reapplication for some of those denied admission since aug 15 
1988 
according to lautenberg aides the bush administration opposes 
house legislation that restores the entitlement to apply based on 
the presumption of persecution however it backs the senate 
compromise fashioned with cooperation from the state department 
aides said 
</TEXT>
