<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange says it has 
reversed an earlier proposal to ban dual trading in most of its 
markets 
in a letter to its members the exchange thursday said 
acrosstheboard restrictions on the practice would be a serious 
mistake and that the practice should be allowed as long as 
surveillance measures are adequate to detect abuse 
dual trading is the longstanding practice among floor brokers at 
futures exchanges of trading for their own accounts and their 
customers 
the practice came under fire after the disclosure in january of 
a federal investigation of suspected trading fraud at the chicago 
merc and the chicago board of trade the worlds two largest 
futures exchanges 
critics say dual trading presents opportunities for floor 
brokers to put their own interests ahead of their customers by 
trading for their own accounts ahead of large customer orders that 
they know will move the market 
a blueribbon committee appointed by the merc to investigate 
trading practices proposed on april 19 that the exchange do away 
with dual trading in all markets except those where it is needed to 
maintain market liquidity 
but after reviewing the proposal the exchanges internal 
committee on dual trading recommended that the practice be allowed 
in any market in which federal regulators determine that the 
exchanges computerized tradereconstruction system produces an 
audit trail that is verifiably accurate to the nearest minute 90 
percent of the time 
</TEXT>
