<DOCNO> AP890721-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
municipal bond investors finally may be coming 
out from the dark 
unlike buyers of corporate and treasury bonds municipal bond 
buyers have no central place to turn to find out current trading 
prices of their investments 
newspapers rarely print lists of municipal bond prices and 
those lists that are available contain only a fraction of the 1 
million or more muni bond issues outstanding 
municipal bond investors also dont benefit from the disclosure 
rules that apply to corporate bond issuers these rules require 
release of detailed financial and background information so that 
corporate bond buyers can make an informed investment 
but several efforts under way could change all that 
late last month the securities and exchange commission approved 
the first formal disclosure rules for municipal bonds the rules 
grew out of the agencys fiveyear investigation of the 225 
billion bond default by the washington public power supply system 
the largest bond default in municipal bond history 
the new rules effective jan 1 will require brokerages 
underwriting municipal bond issues exceeding 1 million in value to 
obtain extensive information about the projects being financed the 
government agencies issuing the bonds and any foreseeable risks 
the bond underwriters then must release this information to all 
potential buyers in the form of official statements during a 
certain time period after the bonds are issued 
the sec rules also encourage the development of a central 
repository that would hold and distribute bond disclosure 
information that would make it easier for municipal bond investors 
to research before they buy 
on another front a trade group is studying the feasibility of 
devising a system to make municipal bond price information readily 
available to retail buyers possibly through a computer network 
similar to the one used for overthecounter stocks 
when investors in the 760 billion municipal bond market want 
to know what their bonds are worth they probably wont find them 
listed in the local newspaper the public securities association 
said in announcing a task force to study a pricing system 
instead investors must call their brokers who may or may not 
have the information at their fingertips said the psa which 
represents banks dealers and brokers that underwrite and sell 
municipal and us government bonds 
but establishing a system to provide trading prices wont be 
easy in part due to the vast number of muni bonds said psa 
president heather l ruth 
another problem she said is that many of the smaller bond 
issues such as those from regional school districts or smalltown 
sewer authorities are not actively traded that means it would be 
hard to establish a trading price if the bonds rarely change hands 
because of this any pricing system most likely would be limited 
to the most actively traded bonds ms ruth said it also may rely 
on indexes of similar kinds of bonds to show representative prices 
rather than prices of individual issues she added 
ms ruth said that despite the absence of disclosure 
requirements most of the larger municipal bond issuers such as 
state governments have provided detailed background information 
for years 
she said the neardefault by the city of new york on billions of 
dollars worth of bonds in the mid1970s was the catalyst for this 
practice 
before the crisis municipal bond issuers typically prepared 
only a one or twopage statement describing new bond offerings 
which was really a sales document ms ruth said 
but new yorks fiscal problems left a bad taste in the mouths of 
municipal bond investors prompting the major issuers to provide 
detailed reports on new issues she said the effect of the sec 
rules will be to spread this practice throughout the muni bond 
market she added 
municipal bonds were exempted from disclosure requirements when 
the sec was established in 1934 however they were not exempted 
from the antifraud regulations of the sec statute which bar bond 
dealers from providing misleading information to customers 
muni bonds were left out of the disclosure requirements for 
several reasons ms ruth said 
for one she said the default rate on municipal securities 
has always been extraordinarily low as compared with corporate 
securities 
another reason was concern that congress would be overstepping 
its bounds if it regulated how state and local goverments raise 
funds she said in addition most municipal bonds were owned by 
institutional investors who were thought to be savvy about the 
risks 
but the new york city crisis and the subsequent wppss default 
changed all that 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
