soybean futures prices fell modestly friday on the chicago board 
of trade while an executive of the italian firm ferruzzi 
finanziaria spa said the exchange had put the soybean market 
in serious trouble by forcing traders to liquidate their 
holdings 
analysts attributed fridays price decline more to improved 
growing conditions than to the ongoing dispute between ferruzzi and 
the exchange 
corn and wheat futures finished mixed in quiet trading 
on other markets porkbelly futures prices fell sharply while 
livestock futures were mixed precious metals advanced and crude 
oil futures declined 
soybeans settled 3 cents to 7 cents lower with the contract 
for delivery in august at 673 a bushel wheat was 2 cents lower 
to cent higher with september at 395 a bushel corn was cent 
lower to 1 cent higher with september at 239 a bushel and oats 
were 1 cents to 2 cents lower with september at 150 a bushel 
analysts said four days of showers in the western corn belt had 
revived corn and soybean crops and forecasts for the coming week 
predicted no return to the withering heat of late june and early 
july 
news that federal regulators had ordered ferruzzi to reduce its 
holdings in the nowexpired july futures contract last week also 
weighed on the soybean market prompting worries that ferruzzi 
might be forced to reduce its reputedly sizeable position in the 
august contract 
but ted mao a grain specialist in new york with shearson lehman 
hutton inc said the ferruzzi news was a minor factor in fridays 
market 
the market in general has been responding to better weather 
he said 
in des moines iowa ferruzzi executive david swanson urged an 
audience of more than 1700 soybean producers and traders to form a 
committee to study and improve the chicago board of trade 
today as we are well aware the market is in serious 
trouble swanson president of ferruzzis central soya co 
subsidiary told the annual convention of the american soybean 
association 
the board of trade issued an emergency order july 11 requiring 
traders to reduce their holdings in the july soybean contract to 1 
million bushels prior to the contracts expiration the contract 
expired on thursday 
the order was widely seen as a move to prevent ferruzzi from 
cornering the soybean market a charge the company denies 
board of trade chairman karsten mahlmann told the soybean 
growers that the exchange took the action to prevent defaults on 
contracts to deliver soybeans without the order the board has 
said obligations to deliver soybeans might have outnumbered the 
supply of deliverable soybeans 
frozen porkbelly futures prices fell sharply on the chicago 
mercantile exchange erasing the previous days gains and a 
government report released after the close of trading left analysts 
divided on the markets likely future course 
